We can model this with sets:
H = { all hurricanes }
S = { all storms }
D = { destructive storms }
Then we have a containment relationship between the sets: H ⊆ S, and S ∩ D ≠ Ø, so if S ∩ D ≠ Ø then H ∩ D ≠ Ø by containment. The premise that "some storms are destructive" is equivalent to S ∩ D ≠ Ø.
Therefore the conclusion follows: some hurricanes are destructive. QED.
In more detail: let h be any element of H. Then since h is a member of every superset of H (by definition), in particular it's an element of S, the universal set of storms. Therefore each h is both a hurricane and a storm. If any storm is destructive, and h is one such storm (because h is both a hurricane and a storm), then it follows logically that some hurricanes are also destructive. The logic works regardless of whether there actually exist any hurricanes; it only requires that our definitions not lead to contradictions, which they don't here. For example, suppose there were no actual storms but we still defined the predicate P(x) = x is a storm, and also P(x) = for all x, x is green. We could validly deduce that there must exist at least one green storm because the intersection of the two properties cannot be empty. In practice of course neither property has any examples, but that doesn't affect the validity of the deductive reasoning itself.

