Let E = {eagles}
B = {birds}
P = {predators}.
Statement: Every element in P is an element of B, thus every element in P is also an element of E (since E ⊆ B).
The statement does not require ignoring domain knowledge, but rather uses it to establish that any bird which is a predator must be an eagle. The argument would be valid only if we knew all birds were eagles. In general, there exist birds which are not eagles, so this statement cannot be generalized into "All birds which are predators are eagles.". To use set theory to determine whether some eagles are predators without invoking domain knowledge one could perform a statistical analysis of the subset P ∩ E of predators which are eagles, however such information was not given with the original question.
Here are three possible sets:
E = {{golden_eagle}, { bald_eagle}}
B = {{ostrich}, {hummingbird}, {hawk}, {penguin}, {condor}}
P = {{redtail_hawk}, {peregrine_falcon}, {barn_owl}}
Some examples where a bird is NOT an eagle include ostrich, hummingbird, penguin, condor, redtail hawk, peregrine falcon, barn owl. Examples where an eagle IS a predator includes golden_eagle, bald_eagle. It can be seen from these examples that E is a proper subset of B and that P is disjoint from both E and B. Therefore, there exists no bird which belongs to both E and P, and hence there are no eagles which are predators.
